-------- Original Message --------
Subject: RE: [IAB] Internal WG Review: IPv6 over Networks of 
Resource-constrained Nodes	(6lo)
Date: Fri, 6 Sep 2013 20:51:27 +0000
From: Dave Thaler <dthaler@microsoft.com>
To: iesg@ietf.org <iesg@ietf.org>, iab@iab.org <iab@iab.org>

I have one concern about the proposed charter.

To repeat what I said in my BOF evaluation, attached:
> Another aspect of the scope discussion was the relationship between this BOF
> and what is in scope of 6man (other IP-over-Foo mechanisms), where the proposed
> 6lo charter makes constrained node networks in scope for 6lo and leaves the rest
> for 6man.   My own take is that I agree with the goal to keep architectural impact out
> of 6lo (but in 6man instead) and as such, 6lo should be scoped to things where the
> architecture doesnt change from existing RFCs (whether 6lowpans architectural
> model or the Ethernet architectural model).  This is narrower than the definition
> of constrained node network.  If the scope is really constrained node network
> then I dont think they can (or should) avoid a discussion of architectural model
> whenever someone comes in with a doc on a constrained node network that
> cant completely emulate Ethernet or 6lowpans model.

The proposed charter below keeps all "constrained node networks" in 
scope and
does explain that

> For adaptation layer
> specifications that do not have implications on IPv6 architecture, 6man will be
> notified about 6Lo's working group last call. Specifications that might have
> such an impact (e.g., by using IPv6 addresses in a specific way or by
> introducing new ND options) will be closely coordinated with 6man, and/or
> specific parts will be fanned out to 6man documents.

However, I don't think it's specific enough about what are "implications 
on IPv6
architecture".  I think it should explicitly say something like:

> For adaptation layer
> specifications that do not have implications on IPv6 architecture
> (and expose to IPv6 the same type of link as used by either Ethernet or 6lowpan),

Or equivalent.   Otherwise, someone will subtly change the link model 
and claim
it has no implications on IPv6 architecture because it doesn't use IPv6 
addresses
in any specific way or use any new ND options.

-Dave

