I attended the 6lo BOF that discussed IPv6 over networks of resource-constr=
ained nodes. This was a WG-forming BOF, and it was explained that this BOF =
is sort of a successor to the half-closed (draining output queue, no input)=
 6lowpan WG which I understood was scoped to a particular link technology (=
802.15.4).  The 6lo BOF on the other hand discussed applicability of the sa=
me protocol solutions to other similar link types (G.9959, RS485, etc.).  T=
here seemed to be general agreement that the 6lowpan mechanisms include a n=
umber of modules, and those modules could be individually reused.  There wa=
s a question about whether an architectural description would be in scope, =
and there seemed to be general agreement to not do so in the proposed WG, b=
ut rather only refer to what 6lowpan already did.  That seems like a good i=
dea to me as long as all the link types that 6lo would do are very similar =
to 802.15.4. That is, I think it might be good to scope a 6lo WG as such.



One of the scope discussions in the BOF was about the use of the term "cons=
trained node network" throughout the proposed charter and what that was (e.=
g., I asked if a carrier pigeon network was one :)   The LWIG WG has a term=
inology doc<http://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-ietf-lwig-terminology> that de=
fines it, and it was agreed to incorporate the definition into the proposed=
 charter.   Another aspect of the scope discussion was the relationship bet=
ween this BOF and what is in scope of 6man (other IP-over-Foo mechanisms), =
where the proposed 6lo charter makes "constrained node networks" in scope f=
or 6lo and leaves the rest for 6man.   My own take is that I agree with the=
 goal to keep architectural impact out of 6lo (but in 6man instead) and as =
such, 6lo should be scoped to things where the architecture doesn't change =
from existing RFCs (whether 6lowpan's architectural model or the Ethernet a=
rchitectural model).  This is narrower than the definition of "constrained =
node network".  If the scope is really "constrained node network" then I do=
n't think they can (or should) avoid a discussion of architectural model wh=
enever someone comes in with a doc on a "constrained node network" that can=
't completely emulate Ethernet or 6lowpan's model.



At the end of the BOF, the chairs poll the room on a number of questions:

1)      Should the IETF address a problem here?  There was strong support f=
or yes.

2)      Do folks agree with the proposed charter (with some mods as discuss=
ed during the meeting)?  Again strong support for yes.

3)      Are there people willing to do work?   There were 30-ish hands for =
willing to comment on docs.  There were 10-ish hands for willing to edit do=
cs.  There were 25-ish hands for willing to implement docs.



So it seemed to me that this is about ready to form a WG, and the next step=
 for the IESG is to decide an appropriate scope.



-Dave


