Good, thanks.


> ****
>
> ** **
>
> But please understand that, per my Discuss on the LWIG terminology I-D, I
> find the definition of a constrained node in that document rather poor.
>

I just read the text of your DISCUSS on that document.


> ****
>
> ** **
>
> I am beginning to sense "I can't describe a constrained node, but I know
> one when I see one."****
>
> ** **
>
> My suggestion for resolving that part of my Discuss is to remove the
> formal definition from the text and simply leave a description that will
> make it clear what is intended. That might be a better approach in this
> charter as well.
>

It surprises me that we already have multiple WG working on constrained
nodes and constrained networks, e.g., ROLL, CORE, LWIG, MANET, but just now
we start setting boundaries for when a node/network is "constrained".
Moreover, there seems to be some vague separation in the IETF between
"constrained" (e.g., MANET) and "more constrained" (e.g., ROLL).
To me, the term LLN has a lot of similarities with "constrained node
network". As the definition of LLN is in the (approved) charter of ROLL, is
the wording in that charter something that we can reuse? (apart from the
focus on routing)


Best regards
Ulrich


