On Sep 9, 2013, at 17:43, Ulrich Herberg <ulrich@herberg.name> wrote:

> To me, the term LLN has a lot of similarities with "constrained node =
network". As the definition of LLN is in the (approved) charter of ROLL, =
is the wording in that charter something that we can reuse? (apart from =
the focus on routing)

Let's see:

> Generally speaking,

Hmm.

> LLNs have at least five distinguishing
> characteristics:
> - LLNs operate with a hard, very small bound on state.

This does fit quite well with constrained nodes.

> - In most cases, LLN optimize for saving energy.

In most cases, this fits well, too.
(Most networks are starting to do this a bit as well, though.)

> - Typical traffic patterns are not simply unicast flows (e.g. in some
> cases most if not all traffic can be point to multipoint).

I don't know what is distinguishing here.

> - In most cases, LLNs will be employed over link layers with=20
> restricted frame-sizes, thus a routing protocol for LLNs should be
> specifically
> adapted for such link layers.

In many cases, this fits well, too, but it is not exactly a =
distinguishing characteristic of the 6lo adaptation layers (other =
adaptation layers do segmentation/fragmentation, and not all 6lo ones =
will need to).

> - LLN routing protocols have to be very careful when trading off
> efficiency for generality; many LLN nodes do not have resources to=20
> waste.

This is one of the main considerations for protocols in a constrained =
node network, so it does apply to adaptation layer specifications as =
well.  I'm not sure that it doesn't also apply to, say, 10 gig Ethernet.

The main point about 6lo is that it is connecting specific link layer =
technologies that have been developed for constrained node networks.  It =
is not a prerequisite for a node itself to actually be constrained to =
take part in a 6lo network, but it is an objective that, as well as the =
link layer technology, the adaptation layer *can* be implemented on a =
constrained node.

Gr=FC=DFe, Carsten


