In many cases, this fits well, too, but it is not exactly a distinguishing =
characteristic of the 6lo adaptation layers (other adaptation layers do seg=
mentation/fragmentation, and not all 6lo ones will need to).<br>
<br>
&gt; - LLN routing protocols have to be very careful when trading off<br>
&gt; efficiency for generality; many LLN nodes do not have resources to<br>
&gt; waste.<br>
<br>
This is one of the main considerations for protocols in a constrained node =
network, so it does apply to adaptation layer specifications as well. =A0I&=
#39;m not sure that it doesn&#39;t also apply to, say, 10 gig Ethernet.<br>

<br>
The main point about 6lo is that it is connecting specific link layer techn=
ologies that have been developed for constrained node networks. =A0It is no=
t a prerequisite for a node itself to actually be constrained to take part =
in a 6lo network, but it is an objective that, as well as the link layer te=
chnology, the adaptation layer *can* be implemented on a constrained node.<=
br>

<br>
Gr=FC=DFe, Carsten<br>
<br>
</blockquote></div><br></div>

