On Sep 9, 2013, at 20:45, Ulrich Herberg <ulrich@herberg.name> wrote:

> I wonder if the term constrained node network (CNN) is actually 100% =
equivalent to LLN (in which case we may not need to create another term; =
in particular one that sounds like a TV channel ;-) Or are there =
differences between the two terms?

Well, the terms do overlap in usage, but that doesn't mean they are =
redundant.

The term "low-power lossy networks" focuses on two aspects of =
constrainedness:

-- low-power (which might be a proxy to constrainedness in energy =
usage), and
-- lossy (which might express one aspect of the constrainedness of the =
network).

The way the term is used also seems to include other aspects, such as =
mostly-static topologies with high fluctuation in packet delivery rate, =
scaling up high-power radio networks, collection tree flows.
The term does not express the other dimensions of constrainedness of the =
nodes themselves, which is really the motivating factor for many things =
we do in the constrained node networks space.
Copying over the old LLN text and using it as a definition of =
constrained node networks would be a serious regression; we have arrived =
at a much better understanding already.
Saying that 6lo is about LLNs also is confusing, because I don't think =
we want to address WiFi, BNEP-style Bluetooth or the Ethernet-like forms =
of PLC.

(I never use the abbreviation, so I don't care about the TV channel.)

Gr=FC=DFe, Carsten


