Hi,
 
I think you have hit on a key point. The LWIG document appears to make an
attempt to redefine the concept of constrained node, and that runs up against
existing definitions.
 
Actually, that may be harsh! LWIG is trying to define the term, and (as you
note) previous usages have been somewhat vague. Unfortunately (IMHO) the attempt
in LWIG to meet the challenge head on has resulted in a rather vague definition.

 
We could:
a. Work together on the LWIG definition and then re-use it for the 6lo charter
b. Come up with a concise definition for the 6lo charter
 
I think b) would be faster and better. 
 
Looking at the definition in ROLL I find draft-ietf-roll-terminology that says
"An LLN is typically composed of many embedded devices with limited power,
memory, and processing resources interconnected by a variety of links." That
would certainly cover it (there is nothing specific about routing in that
definition), but it might also be nice to replace "a variety of links" with
something a bit more specific. That would cut into my other concern about which
(or what type of) links this work is intended to cover.
 
Cheers,
Adrian
 
From: Ulrich Herberg [mailto:ulrich@herberg.name] 
Sent: 09 September 2013 16:44
To: adrian@olddog.co.uk
Cc: Ralph Droms; Haberman Brian; The IESG; 6lo@ietf.org
Subject: Re: [6lo] Adrian Farrel's Block on charter-ietf-6lo-00-00: (with BLOCK
and COMMENT)
 
Hi Adrian,
 
On Sat, Sep 7, 2013 at 12:06 PM, Adrian Farrel <adrian@olddog.co.uk> wrote:
Hi Ulrich,
 
Sorry for the delay while travelling.
 
I *do* believe that explicitly stating the definition of Constrained Things in
the charter text will be a very positive step.
 
Good, thanks.
 
 
But please understand that, per my Discuss on the LWIG terminology I-D, I find
the definition of a constrained node in that document rather poor.
 
I just read the text of your DISCUSS on that document. 
 
 
I am beginning to sense "I can't describe a constrained node, but I know one
when I see one."
 
My suggestion for resolving that part of my Discuss is to remove the formal
definition from the text and simply leave a description that will make it clear
what is intended. That might be a better approach in this charter as well.
 
It surprises me that we already have multiple WG working on constrained nodes
and constrained networks, e.g., ROLL, CORE, LWIG, MANET, but just now we start
setting boundaries for when a node/network is "constrained". Moreover, there
seems to be some vague separation in the IETF between "constrained" (e.g.,
MANET) and "more constrained" (e.g., ROLL).
To me, the term LLN has a lot of similarities with "constrained node network".
As the definition of LLN is in the (approved) charter of ROLL, is the wording in
that charter something that we can reuse? (apart from the focus on routing)


Best regards
Ulrich
 
 
From: Ulrich Herberg [mailto:ulrich@herberg.name] 
Sent: 03 September 2013 17:34
To: adrian@olddog.co.uk
Cc: Ralph Droms; Haberman Brian; The IESG; 6lo@ietf.org

Subject: Re: [6lo] Adrian Farrel's Block on charter-ietf-6lo-00-00: (with BLOCK
and COMMENT)
 
Adrian,

as a first step towards resolving your "Block", would you agree if we copy the
current definitions of Constrained Node, Constrained Network and Constrained
Node Network from the LWIG draft into the charter, instead of citing the draft
or referring to the LWIG work in general? 
Best regards
Ulrich
 
On Sun, Sep 1, 2013 at 10:53 AM, Adrian Farrel <adrian@olddog.co.uk> wrote:
All, 
 
I really want to get out of the way of this work.
 
I understand that the proposed wording:
- does not preclude the necessary work being done in 6man
- does not stop any of the intended work being done in 6lo
 
Both of these are good objectives.
 
My concern is that the wording does not prevent other work being done in 6lo
that has not been dreamed of and would be out of scope if we could dream of it.
I am probably *way* too paranoid, but I am trying to find a form that scopes in
the work you want to do *and* scopes out the work you have no intention of
doing.
 
Happy to hear any other suggestions.
Thanks,
Adrian
 
From: Ulrich Herberg [mailto:ulrich@herberg.name] 
Sent: 29 August 2013 17:02
To: Ralph Droms
Cc: Haberman Brian; Farrel Adrian; iesg@ietf.org IESG; 6lo@ietf.org
Subject: Re: [6lo] Adrian Farrel's Block on charter-ietf-6lo-00-00: (with BLOCK
and COMMENT)
 
I agree with Ralph and Brian (on both points).

Ulrich
 
On Wed, Aug 28, 2013 at 2:47 PM, Ralph Droms <rdroms.ietf@gmail.com> wrote:

On Aug 28, 2013, at 1:17 PM 8/28/13, Brian Haberman <brian@innovationslab.net>
wrote:

> Adrian,
>
> On 8/28/13 3:56 PM, Adrian Farrel wrote:
>> Hi again,
>>
>> You say that the distinction between 6lo and 6man is drawn based on where the
>> 6LoWPAN RFCs are applicable.
>> Is it necessary to say, in the charter, where those RFCs are applicable?
>>
>> Currently there is an attempt via "for link layer technologies of interest in
>> constrained node networks." But maybe you would only use the 6LoWPAN RFCs in
>> environments where they are applicable, in which case we can resolve by
changing
>> to say...
>>
>> OLD
>> 6Lo focuses on Internet Area work that is needed for constrained node
>> networks, as the term is defined by the LWIG working group.
>> NEW
>> 6Lo focuses on Internet Area work that is needed for IPv6 adaptation
>> using technologies previously described by the 6LoWPAN working group.
>> END
>>
>
> The above is fine with me.  I will wait to see if there are objections from
the mailing list.
Looking at the list of candidate documents from Carsten's BoF presentation, this
revised text looks OK.  It fits around those candidate documents, as long as
"technologies previously described by the 6LoWPAN working group" is interpreted
liberally enough to allow modifications to the technologies as required by the
specific adaptation.

>
>> and
>>
>> OLD
>> 1. IPv6-over-foo adaptation layer specifications using 6LoWPAN technologies
>> (RFC4944, RFC6282, RFC6775) for link layer technologies of interest in
>> constrained node networks
>> NEW
>> 1. IPv6-over-foo adaptation layer specifications using 6LoWPAN technologies
>> (RFC4944, RFC6282, RFC6775).
>> END
>
> So, *I* think this change is a little problematic.  As a data point, there are
components of the 6LoWPAN work that are being proposed for inclusion in the base
IPv6 specifications (e.g., draft-chakrabarti-nordmark-6man-efficient-nd).  That
draft takes changes made to NDP for these "constrained node networks" and
applies them to all link layers, including Ethernet.  Dropping that descriptor
from the charter would essentially allow 6lo to work on any link layer
technology.
Again reviewing Carsten's presentation, the original text would not conflict
with the list of documents proposed for consideration in 6lo, and I agree with
Brian that work like draft-chakrabarti-nordmark-6man-efficient-nd, which applies
to all link layers, should stay in 6man.

>
> Regards,
> Brian

