Hi Samita,

Comments inline.

To summarise: I think we are going around in circles re. "constrained" 
terms and I support Ulrich's suggestion to copy the terms from 
draft-ietf-lwig-terminology verbatim.

Robert

On 31/08/2013 02:14, Samita Chakrabarti wrote:
> Hi All,
>
> There have been a lot of discussion in the list and I am catching up with
them.
>
> Here are some proposed text for the charter and some thoughts ( as per the
following email  from Brian ) .
>
> CURRENT
>
>
>   6Lo focuses on Internet Area work that is needed for constrained node
> networks, as the term is defined by the LWIG working group.
>
> NEW:
>
> 6Lo focuses on Internet Area work that is needed for constrained node
Networks. The constrained node networks have  limited functionality compared
to the  common IP networks composed of line-powered and high-capacity
devices. An example of constrained networks is IPv6 over IEEE
802.15.4(6LoWPAN).
> The constrained nodes can be characterized by many different categories
such as node capability, cost of networks, media constraints, regulatory
limits, bit-rates etc.
<RCC>I think we are going around in circles here. I support Ulrich's 
suggestion to simply copy the definitions from 
draft-ietf-lwig-terminology. On the basis that it is almost impossible 
to provide a definitive objective statement about what a "constrained" 
anything is, I think the terms in draft-ietf-lwig-terminology are well 
considered and well qualified. Whilst the qualifications are dealt with 
more in the LWIG WG, the charter states that there will be coordination 
with LWIG, so I don't see what else needs to be done for this.</RCC>
>
>
> CURRENT
> 6Lo works on small, focused pieces of Internet Area work. 6Lo does not
take on
> larger cross-layer efforts. The working group will continue to reuse
existing
> protocols and mechanisms whenever reasonable and possible.
>
> QUESTION:  Would like to know what we mean by "small focused pieces of
Internet Area work" ?
>
> Would it be better to say "6Lo will work on focused pieces of Internet
Area for which the work already started
> on the IPv6-over-foo and provide generic guidelines for IPv6 running on
constrained link-layers".
<RCC>The suggested text seems to preclude starting work for other 
as-yet-to-be-determined link layers applicable to constrained node 
networks, which would not be the case, surely? "small, focused pieces of 
Internet Area work" is clear enough to me.</RCC>
>
> Will this group develop any work on provisioning of the constrained nodes?
Gateway devices between Internet (IPv6) and  constrained networks?
> If so,  it would be good to clarify them.
<RCC>Given the statement regarding security and management, I would 
think not</RCC>
>
> CURRENT:
> Security and management work that is not specific to the link layers being
> worked on is out of scope.
>
> QUESTION: Is it trying to say?
>
> Any new security and management work that is not specific to the
constrained link, is out of scope.
> This sentence is not clear to me.
<RCC>
I would rather not bring in another "constrained" term here. I think the 
sentence as it stands is OK - a possible change which may clarify would 
be something like:

"Security and management work that is not specific to the link layers 
under consideration is out of scope."
</RCC>
>
>
> The rest looks fine to me.
>
> Thanks,
> -Samita
