well.

It surprises me that we already have multiple WG working on constrained nod=
es and constrained networks, e.g., ROLL, CORE, LWIG, MANET, but just now we=
 start setting boundaries for when a node/network is "constrained". Moreove=
r, there seems to be some vague separation in the IETF between "constrained=
" (e.g., MANET) and "more constrained" (e.g., ROLL).
To me, the term LLN has a lot of similarities with "constrained node networ=
k". As the definition of LLN is in the (approved) charter of ROLL, is the w=
ording in that charter something that we can reuse? (apart from the focus o=
n routing)


Best regards
Ulrich


From: Ulrich Herberg [mailto:ulrich@herberg.name<mailto:ulrich@herberg.name=
>]
Sent: 03 September 2013 17:34
To: adrian@olddog.co.uk<mailto:adrian@olddog.co.uk>
Cc: Ralph Droms; Haberman Brian; The IESG; 6lo@ietf.org<mailto:6lo@ietf.org=
>

Subject: Re: [6lo] Adrian Farrel's Block on charter-ietf-6lo-00-00: (with B=
LOCK and COMMENT)

Adrian,

as a first step towards resolving your "Block", would you agree if we copy =
the current definitions of Constrained Node, Constrained Network and Constr=
ained Node Network from the LWIG draft into the charter, instead of citing =
the draft or referring to the LWIG work in general?
Best regards
Ulrich

On Sun, Sep 1, 2013 at 10:53 AM, Adrian Farrel <adrian@olddog.co.uk<mailto:=
adrian@olddog.co.uk>> wrote:
All,

I really want to get out of the way of this work.

I understand that the proposed wording:
- does not preclude the necessary work being done in 6man
- does not stop any of the intended work being done in 6lo

Both of these are good objectives.

My concern is that the wording does not prevent other work being done in 6l=
o that has not been dreamed of and would be out of scope if we could dream =
of it.
I am probably *way* too paranoid, but I am trying to find a form that scope=
s in the work you want to do *and* scopes out the work you have no intentio=
n of doing.

Happy to hear any other suggestions.
Thanks,
Adrian

