On Wed, Aug 28, 2013 at 2:47 PM, Ralph Droms <rdroms.ietf@gmail.com> wrote:

On Aug 28, 2013, at 1:17 PM 8/28/13, Brian Haberman <brian@innovationslab.net>
wrote:

> Adrian,
>
> On 8/28/13 3:56 PM, Adrian Farrel wrote:
>> Hi again,
>>
>> You say that the distinction between 6lo and 6man is drawn based on where the
>> 6LoWPAN RFCs are applicable.
>> Is it necessary to say, in the charter, where those RFCs are applicable?
>>
>> Currently there is an attempt via "for link layer technologies of interest in
>> constrained node networks." But maybe you would only use the 6LoWPAN RFCs in
>> environments where they are applicable, in which case we can resolve by
changing
>> to say...
>>
>> OLD
>> 6Lo focuses on Internet Area work that is needed for constrained node
>> networks, as the term is defined by the LWIG working group.
>> NEW
>> 6Lo focuses on Internet Area work that is needed for IPv6 adaptation
>> using technologies previously described by the 6LoWPAN working group.
>> END
>>
>
> The above is fine with me.  I will wait to see if there are objections from
the mailing list.
Looking at the list of candidate documents from Carsten's BoF presentation, this
revised text looks OK.  It fits around those candidate documents, as long as
"technologies previously described by the 6LoWPAN working group" is interpreted
liberally enough to allow modifications to the technologies as required by the
specific adaptation.

>
>> and
>>
>> OLD
>> 1. IPv6-over-foo adaptation layer specifications using 6LoWPAN technologies
>> (RFC4944, RFC6282, RFC6775) for link layer technologies of interest in
>> constrained node networks
>> NEW
>> 1. IPv6-over-foo adaptation layer specifications using 6LoWPAN technologies
>> (RFC4944, RFC6282, RFC6775).
>> END
>
> So, *I* think this change is a little problematic.  As a data point, there are
components of the 6LoWPAN work that are being proposed for inclusion in the base
IPv6 specifications (e.g., draft-chakrabarti-nordmark-6man-efficient-nd).  That
draft takes changes made to NDP for these "constrained node networks" and
applies them to all link layers, including Ethernet.  Dropping that descriptor
from the charter would essentially allow 6lo to work on any link layer
technology.
Again reviewing Carsten's presentation, the original text would not conflict
with the list of documents proposed for consideration in 6lo, and I agree with
Brian that work like draft-chakrabarti-nordmark-6man-efficient-nd, which applies
to all link layers, should stay in 6man.

>
> Regards,
> Brian

- Ralph

